Histological findings were mainly prominent in the gastrointestinal tract and spleen. Almost all the rabbits (6/7) had lesions in duodenum, jejunum, and ileum with varying degrees of severity (Table 1
). In the caecum there was far less damage in the epithelium. Epithelial lesions of the small intestine were mainly atrophy and fusion of villi, and slight to moderate diffuse infiltration of lymphocytes and plasma cells along the mucosa. Different intestinal lesions observed in some rabbits are depicted in Fig. 1
.
